UPDATE: Many of you are already aware Governor Dewine announced that all Ohio schools will be on a 3 week ‚ÄúSpring Break‚Äù due to COVID-19. This will take effect at the end of the day on Monday, March 16 thru April 3. Please be patient with us as we wait for more clarification from the Governor‚Äôs Office. The health and well-being of our students, staff, and families will always be our number one priority. Again we ask for your patience and understanding. In addition you will most likely hear about these events through news outlets before you hear directly from the district, as these directives are coming from state government. We will then put together details for our specific district and send out to our families. Please be patient we will provide more info when we have it.
*Currently there is a technical issue with our system that sends email blasts, some of you may not have received the 2PM email(this is being worked on).

HEALTH REMINDERS: The Canal Winchester School District follows the recommendations of the Ohio Department of Health and the CDC to control the spread of disease in schools. Remind your children of the following steps as these are some of the most effective way of preventing the spread of illness:
‚Ä¢ Washing hands
‚Ä¢ Using hand sanitizer
‚Ä¢ Avoid touching eyes, mouth, nose until hands washed
‚Ä¢ Avoid contact with sick people
‚Ä¢ Stay home when sick
‚Ä¢ Cover mouth/nose w/ tissue or sleeve when coughing or sneezing
‚Ä¢ Get proper amount of sleep and eat well balanced meals to build healthy immune system
Please notify your school when your child contracts a communicable disease such as the flu or strep throat, head lice, or scabies so that steps can be taken to control the spread of these conditions to other students
When Should I Keep My Child Home from School? See Chart

ROCK STAR TEACHER @ CWHS!!! CONGRATS!!
On behalf of Cisco Networking Academy, our own Mrs. Sandy Thomaschek, has been awarded the 2019 Quarterly Regional Spotlight Award for achievements in Ohio. (She was the only one selected in the US and Canada) This award recognizes the valuable contributions of NetAcad Instructors and the impact they have on the students of Cisco Networking Academy and the program overall.
The efforts at Canal Winchester have created tremendous opportunities in Ohio:
‚Ä¢ Outstanding performance and consistently growing the Cisco Networking Academy and the program over the past five years
‚Ä¢ Going above and beyond to promote the CCNA Routing and Switching curricula using a blended learning approach that ensures the students success
‚Ä¢ Orchestrating students to participate in Skills-USA and BPA events which have won at both state and National levels
‚Ä¢ Enriching students with foundational technologies and relevant skill sets for adoption of next generation technologies

ROCK STAR TEACHER @ CWHS!!! CONGRATS!!
On behalf of Cisco Networking Academy, our own Mrs. Sandy Thomaschek, has been awarded the 2019 Quarterly Regional Spotlight Award for achievements in Ohio. (She was the only one selected in the US and Canada) This award recognizes the valuable contributions of NetAcad Instructors and the impact they have on the students of Cisco Networking Academy and the program overall.
The efforts at Canal Winchester have created tremendous opportunities in Ohio:
‚Ä¢ Outstanding performance and consistently growing the Cisco Networking Academy and the program over the past five years
‚Ä¢ Going above and beyond to promote the CCNA Routing and Switching curricula using a blended learning approach that ensures the students success
‚Ä¢ Orchestrating students to participate in Skills-USA and BPA events which have won at both state and National levels
‚Ä¢ Enriching students with foundational technologies and relevant skill sets for adoption of next generation technologies

post_text:
Over the last year students, community members and staff put together a "Portrait of a Graduate" as we empower all students for success it means more than academic achievement. The portrait describes the skills, attributes and character traits we believe our students need for life beyond graduation. Our goal is to develop the whole child: Academically, mentally, socially, and behaviorally. The 6 themes are focused on: In no particular order, all are important
1. Respectful Citizens
2. Problem Solver
3. Self-Aware Individuals
4. Responsible Learners
5. Collaborators
6. Communicators

Reminder to start the year:
Buses usually run late the first few weeks of school in the morning and during drop-off in the afternoon. Be sure to be at the bus stop 5 minutes early in the morning to help this matter. Also, it always takes more time for students to find their correct bus after school, so please be patient as students and bus drivers are learning names and faces. (Again expect buses to be late the first few weeks of school as students learn new routines.)

post_text: Brett Smithers, working on his Eagle Scout Project, created USA Flag Drop Boxes to serve the United States Flags of Canal Winchester. Their purpose is to provide two locations, the Columbus Metropolitan Library Canal Winchester Branch and the CWLS Elementary Schools, for citizens of our community to drop off torn, faded, old, and tattered USA Flags for collection and proper retirement by Boy Scout Troop 103. These boxes will be readily available to drive by and drop off flags. They can be recognized by their gray color and sign that clearly says ‚ÄúUSA FLAG DROP BOX‚Äù. By taking your flags to these boxes you are not only doing a good deed for the flag, but for all the Americans the flag represents.

post_text: The district will be showing the documentary Most Likely to Succeed on Tuesday, March 7th from 6-8 p.m. at Canal Winchester Middle School. The purpose of this event is to foster meaningful discussion among educators, administrators, parents, students, and the community about how current obstacles can be overcome and steps towards change can be taken on a local level. This event is open to the public. Please visit http://www.mltsfilm.org/ for more information about the film and movement. Due to the nature of the film (90min with small group discussion after) it is suggested for adults and students of middle school age and older if they would like to participate. Spread the word and bring a friend.
